					<DIV CLASS=3DRedHeading>
						PRESENTED BY KIRSTY WARK
					</DIV>
=09=09=09=09=09
=09=09=09=09=09
<br>
And then on Review, I'll be joined by Mark Kermode, Bidisha, Peter Whittle =
and Dotun Adebayo to review a film already hailed as a classic.=20=20
<br>
=20
<br>
<b>THIS IS ENGLAND</b>
<br>

<br>
Shane Meadows has directed This Is England - a return to the Thatcher era w=
hen the Falklands War was not long over, unemployment was kicking three mil=
lion, there was a skinhead revival and the National Front was recruiting.=
=20
<br>

<br>
This is England is a film about class, race, music, skinheads, New Romantic=
s and belonging. Although not strictly autobiographical, some scenes mirror=
 events in Meadows' life. Like the central character, 12 year old Shaun, pl=
ayed by first timer Thomas Turgoose, Meadows was adopted by a skinhead gang=
 and the film does much to give skinheads their cultural place, rescuing so=
me of them from their violent racist reputation.=20
<br>
=20
<br>
<b>ENGLEBY</b>=20
<br>

<br>
Sebastian Faulks leaves the long ago past behind in his new novel Engleby, =
in which the unreliable, deeply disturbed narrator Mike Engleby takes us in=
to his secretive world, from his unhappy days at boarding school, through h=
is reputation as a misfit at Cambridge to his career as a journalist in Lon=
don in the '80s, to his life now and the demons he has to face.=20
<br>
=20
<br>
<b>CALLED TO ACCOUNT</b>=20
<br>

<br>
"The Indictment of Anthony Charles Lynton Blair For The Crime Of Aggression=
 Against Iraq" is playing at the Tricycle Theatre in London. Entitled Calle=
d to Account, it is the latest collaboration between Richard Norton-Taylor =
and Nicolas Kent who created verbatim theatre pieces such as Nuremberg and =
Bloody Sunday at the theatre.=20
<br>

<br>
This is a departure from that format in that it is an inquiry commissioned =
not by government, but by the theatre. Leading barristers gave their time f=
or free to conduct interviews during last January and February with key fig=
ures including the neocon Richard Perle, the former Weapons Inspector Scott=
 Ritter and the former International Development Secretary Clare Short. The=
se interviews were then edited for the play which is designed as an even ha=
nded inquiry.=20
<br>
=20
<br>
<b>BJORK</b>=20
<br>

<br>
And finally Bjork. Her new album Volta is perhaps her most accessible - it =
certainly could put people on the dance floor. Unlike her last release, thi=
s has a riot of instruments, and some scorching lyrics.=20
<br>
=20
<br>
Do listen in and sing along at 11pm.=20=20=20
<br>

<br>
Kirsty=20
<br>

